Here, "Fushimi Wakamiya" refers to Prince {{ill|Hiroyasu Fushimi|ja|伏見宮博恭王|12=draft}} before inheriting the {{ill|Fushimi-no-miya|ja|伏見宮|12=draft}} title. He succeeded the title in {{ill|1923|ja|1923rd year|12=draft}}.</ref><ref>December 24, 1941, Yomiuri Shimbun: "Kitashirakawa Wakamiya attends the Children's Music Event"</ref>. According to this custom, Prince {{ill|Tomohito|ja|寬仁親王|12=draft}}, the first son of {{ill|Prince Takahito of Mikasa|ja|三笠宮崇仁親王|12=draft}}, would be "'''Mikasa Wakamiya'''", and Prince {{ill|Hisahito|ja|悠仁親王|12=draft}}, the first son of {{ill|Prince Fumihito|ja|秋篠宮文仁親王|12=draft}}, would be "'''Akishino Wakamiya'''." However, this designation is rarely used even among those knowledgeable about the {{ill|Imperial Household|ja|皇室|12=draft}} system today. Instead, it is common to use the {{ill|Miyake|ja|宮号|12=draft}} as if it were a {{ill|surname|ja|名字|12=draft}}. Prince Tomohito expressed his criticism of this practice. {{main|{{ill|Prince Tomohito#Miyake naming conventions|ja|寬仁親王#宮号の有無と表記|12=draft}}}}  

