'''Wakamiya''' (若宮)  
{{TOCright}}  

== Imperial Household ==  
* A child of the {{ill|Imperial Family|ja|皇族|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Family|1=Imperial Family of Japan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11581068}}. Refers to a {{ill|Imperial Prince|ja|皇子|vi|Hoàng tử|zh|皇子|ko|황자|lt=Imperial Prince|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Prince|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} during their childhood.  
* Before {{ill|1947|en|1947|WD=Q5263|lt=1947|1=1947}} ({{ill|Shōwa 22|ja|昭和22年|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa 22|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 1947年|1=1947|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q5263}}), when the {{ill|Ōke|en|Ōke|WD=Q864190|lt=Eleven Miyake|1=Ōke}} renounced their {{ill|Imperial status|ja|皇籍|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial status|1=imperial status|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11581092}}, it was customary to refer to the heir of a {{ill|Miyake|ja|宮家|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyake|1=miyake|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q844727}} head (usually the eldest son) as "'''○○ Wakamiya''' (○○のわかみや)." <ref>May 4, 1895, Yomiuri Shimbun: "The 5th Selected Exhibition Awards Ceremony - Prizes Presented by Kitashirakawa Wakamiya Prince"</ref><ref>May 25, 1907, Asahi Shimbun: "Naming of Fushimi Wakamiya Royal Daughter"  
Here, "Fushimi Wakamiya" refers to Prince {{ill|Prince Fushimi Hiroyasu|en|Prince Fushimi Hiroyasu|WD=Q285846|lt=Hiroyasu Fushimi|1=Prince Fushimi Hiroyasu}} before inheriting the {{ill|Fushimi-no-miya|en|Fushimi-no-miya|WD=Q1038337|lt=Fushimi-no-miya|1=Fushimi-no-miya}} title. He succeeded the title in {{ill|1923|en|1923|WD=Q2169|lt=1923|1=1923}}.</ref><ref>December 24, 1941, Yomiuri Shimbun: "Kitashirakawa Wakamiya attends the Children's Music Event"</ref>. According to this custom, Prince {{ill|Prince Tomohito of Mikasa|en|Prince Tomohito of Mikasa|WD=Q486381|lt=Tomohito|1=Prince Tomohito of Mikasa}}, the first son of {{ill|Takahito, Prince Mikasa|en|Takahito, Prince Mikasa|WD=Q280229|lt=Prince Takahito of Mikasa|1=Takahito, Prince Mikasa}}, would be "'''Mikasa Wakamiya'''", and Prince {{ill|Prince Hisahito of Akishino|en|Prince Hisahito of Akishino|WD=Q844333|lt=Hisahito|1=Prince Hisahito of Akishino}}, the first son of {{ill|Fumihito, Crown Prince of Japan|en|Fumihito, Crown Prince of Japan|WD=Q311174|lt=Prince Fumihito|1=Fumihito, Crown Prince of Japan}}, would be "'''Akishino Wakamiya'''." However, this designation is rarely used even among those knowledgeable about the {{ill|Imperial House of Japan|en|Imperial House of Japan|WD=Q909452|lt=Imperial Household|1=Imperial House of Japan}} system today. Instead, it is common to use the {{ill|Miyake|ja|宮号|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyake|1=miya|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q12250872}} as if it were a {{ill|surname|ja|名字|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/surname|1=myōji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q69634220}}. Prince Tomohito expressed his criticism of this practice. {{main|{{ill|Prince Tomohito#Miyake naming conventions|ja|寬仁親王#宮号の有無と表記|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Tomohito#Miyake naming conventions|1=Prince Tomohito of Mikasa|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q486381}}}}  

